erobic respiration in eukaryotes, rare but there -- t22 Enzymes of anaerobic energy metabolism in algae -- t23 Wax ester fermentation in Euglena gracilis -- t24 Chlamydomonas reinhardtii, a jack of all trades -- t25 Organisms with hydrogenosomes -- t26 Nyctotherus ovalis and H2-producing mitochondria -- t27 Energy metabolism in organisms with mitosomes -- t28 Energy parasites -- tPart III: Evolution -- tIntroduction -- t29 Why did mitochondria become synonymous with O2? -- t30 Ubiquitous mitochondria among anaerobes -- t31 Differential loss from a facultative anaerobic ancestral state -- t32 Oxygen availability in early eukaryote evolution: the Pasteurian -- t33 Evolution with mitochondrial energy metabolism -- t34 Envoi -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMitochondria are sometimes called the powerhouses of eukaryotic cells, because mitochondria are the site of ATP synthesis in the cell. ATP is the universal energy currency, it provides the power that runs all other life processes. Humans need oxygen to survive because of ATP synthesis in mitochondria. The sugars from our diet are converted to carbon dioxide in mitochondria in a process that requires oxygen. Just like a fire needs oxygen to burn, our mitochondria need oxygen to make ATP. From textbooks and popular literature one can easily get the impression that all mitochondria require oxygen. But that is not the case. There are many groups of organismsm known that make ATP in mitochondria without the help of oxygen. They have preserved biochemical relicts from the early evolution of eukaryotic cells, which took place during times in Earth history when there was hardly any oxygen avaiable, certainly not enough to breathe. How the anaerobic forms of mitochondria work, in which organisms they occur, and how the eukaryotic anaerobes that possess them fit into the larger picture of rising atmospheric oxygen during Earth history are the topic of this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEukaryotic cells. 0aMetabolism. 0aMitochondria. 4aEukaryotes. 4aEvolution. 4aMetabolism. 4aMitochondria. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Cell Biology.2bisacsh1 aMentel, Marek, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTielens, Aloysius G. M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070480808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020z9783110704600oZDB-23-DPM0 cEPUBz97831106127210 cprintz978311066677940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311061241740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110612417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110612417.jpg  a978-3-11-065906-1  De Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCb2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070480-8  EBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1b2021  a978-3-11-075072-0  DG Ebook Package English 2021b2021  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK 